comment_data.body: Thanks for the report! I assume that you had a Flutter app running when you saw this issue?
@jacob314, it looks like the `io.flutter.inspector.EvalOnDartLibrary` eval callback is not expecting a sentinel as a response (I _believe_ those are returned when an object has been GC or some such).

Hi @devoncarew Yes, I had the android simulator up and running. I was previously exploring the flutter example projects. Then I opened mine; clicked a couple of files and the IDE reported a crash. Hope this helps üçª

Hey there, I've experienced this one a couple of times today as well.

## What happened

  * Create a new project
  * Mess around with Isolates a bit
  * Hot-Reload and Full-Reload the project a few times as I make adjustments
  * See crash reported in IntelliJ
  * See error count grow rapidly. Stack traces below reduced to only 1, but the report originally included several of the same type.

https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/pull/1980 should greatly reduce the frequency of this issue but it is still possible for this issue to occur. 
I've moved to M24 as the frequency should be sufficiently reduced for it to be a non-issue. To fully eliminate this issue we need to in M24 take the remaining cases where the observatory protocol is used and tweak them so we are not returning any references to String objects that could be garbage collected.
This is fixed by https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/16638 which uses a ring of objects to avoid the issue.
